<subsection xml:id="subsec-performing-chance-experiments-in-different-situations">
    <title>Performing chance experiments in different situations</title>
    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Suppose the bag contains:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>4</m> red counters
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>3</m> blue counters
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>2</m> green counters
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>1</m> yellow counter
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            This makes a total of <m>10</m> counters.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Before drawing, predict how many times you think each color will appear if you draw 20 times, replacing the counter back into the bag after each draw.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Perform the experiment by drawing a counter from the bag, recording its color, and putting it back before drawing again. Repeat <m>20</m> times and fill in the table below.
                    </p>
                    <table>
                        <title></title>
                        <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                            <row halign="left" header="yes">
                                <cell>Color</cell>
                                <cell>Tally Marks</cell>
                                <cell>Actual Count</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>Red</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>Blue</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>Green</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>Green</cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </table>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Repeat the experiment by drawing counters 15 and 30 times.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Analyze:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Which color appeared the most? 
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Which color appeared the least?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Share and compare your findings with other groups.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Chance Experiment}</m> is an activity or situation where the outcome is not certain. You don’t know what will happen until you try it.
    </p>
    <p>
        Each time you do the experiment, you might get a different result, even if the conditions stay the same.
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{ Examples of Chance Experiments:}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Tossing a Coin
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                A coin has <m>2</m> sides: Heads and Tails
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Each side has a <m>1</m> out of <m>2</m> chance <m>(50)</m>%
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Rolling a Die
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                A die has <m>6</m> faces numbered from <m>1</m> to <m>6</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Each number has a <m>1</m> out of <m>6</m> chance
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Picking Counters
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                A bag may have counters of different colors
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The chance of picking a certain color depends on how many of that color are in the bag
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Experiment}</m>: A process that leads to one or more outcomes (e.g., rolling a die)
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{trial}</m>: One performance of the experiment (e.g., one roll of the die)
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{outcome}</m>: The result of a chance experiment.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Probability}</m>: A number that tells how likely an event is to happen, usually between <m>0</m> and <m>1</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>0</m> means it cannot happen
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>1</m> means it is certain to happen
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                A probability of <m>0.5</m> or <m>(50)</m>% means it’s equally likely to happen or not
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Akello has four different T-shirts in her drawer: navy, grey, white, and red. She chooses one T-shirt randomly. What are the possible colours of the T-shirt Akello picked?
            </p>
        </statement> 
        <solution>
            <p>
                The possible colours of the T-shirt Akello picked are: navy, grey, white, red.
            </p>
        </solution>  
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A basket contains <m>4</m> different fruits: apple, banana, peach, and pineapple. One fruit is randomly chosen from the basket.
            </p>
            <p>
                List the sample space of the possible types of fruit that could be chosen.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The sample space of the possible types of fruit is:
            </p>
            <p>
                Sample Space = {apple, banana, peach, pineapple}
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
</subsection>